data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(item)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` (a span method) instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based calls**, so this throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to pick `Enumerable.Contains` by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid.
